8/14/20, 14:24 - +91 84359 34456: #include <bits/stdc++.h> 
  
#define N 3 
using namespace std; 
  
// Returns true if mat[][] is magic 
// square, else returns false. 
bool isMagicSquare(int mat[][N]) 
{  
    // calculate the sum of  
    // the prime diagonal 
    int sum = 0,sum2=0;  
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) 
        sum = sum + mat[i][i]; 
    // the secondary diagonal 
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) 
        sum2 = sum2 + mat[i][N-1-i]; 
  
    if(sum!=sum2)  
        return false; 
  
    // For sums of Rows  
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) { 
          
        int rowSum = 0;      
        for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) 
            rowSum += mat[i][j]; 
          
        // check if every row sum is 
        // equal to prime diagonal sum 
        if (rowSum != sum) 
            return false; 
    } 
  
    // For sums of Columns 
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) { 
          
        int colSum = 0;      
        for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) 
            colSum += mat[j][i]; 
  
        // check if every column sum is  
        // equal to prime diagonal sum 
        if (sum != colSum)  
        return false; 
    } 
  
    return true; 
} 
  
// driver program to  
// test above function 
int main() 
{ 
    int mat[][N] = {{ 2, 7, 6 }, 
                    { 9, 5, 1 }, 
                    { 4, 3, 8 }}; 
      
    if (isMagicSquare(mat)) 
        cout << "Magic Square"; 
    else
        cout << "Not a magic Square"; 
      
    return 0; 
}

8/22/20, 20:39 - +91 90095 03831: #include <stdio.h>
int size=0,sch[29],s1[29],s2[29],s3[29],s4[29],tot[29];
int main()
{
 initialize();
 choose(); 
 return 0;
}
void initialize()
{
  for(int i=0;i<30;i++)
  sch[i]=s1[i]=s2[i]=s3[i]=tot[i]=0;
}
void choose()
{
  int n;
  printf("\nEnter Choice\n");
  printf("1=List All Entries\n");
  printf("2=Insert New Entry\n");
  printf("3=Delete An Entry\n");
  printf("4=Sort All Entries\n");
  printf("5=Search For An Entry\n");
  printf("6=End Program\n");
  scanf("%d",&n);
  switch(n)
  {
    case 1: list();break;
    case 2: insert();break;
    case 3: delete();break;
    case 4: sort();break;
    case 5: search();break;
    default:
    case 6: return;
   }
   choose();
 }
  
void list()
{
  if(size==0)
  printf("No Entries to display");
  else
  {
    printf("Sch.\ts1\ts2\ts3\s4\tTotal\n");
    for(int i=0;i<size;i++)
    printf("%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\n",sch[i],s1[i],s2[i],s3[i],s4[i],tot[i]);
    printf(" End of List\n");
  }
  return;
}
void delete()
{
  int sc,i,j;
  printf("Enter Scholar Number\n");
  scanf("%d",&sc);
  for(i=0;i<size;i++)
  if(sch[i]==sc)
  {
    sch[i]=s1[i]=s2[i]=s3[i]=tot[i]=0;
    for(j=i;j<size;j++)
    {
    sch[j]=sch[j+1];
    s1[j]=s1[j+1];
    s2[j]=s2[j+1];
    s3[j]=s3[j+1];
    s4[j]=s4[j+1];
    tot[j]=tot[j+1];
    }
    size--;
    printf("Entry Deleted Successfully\n");
    return;
  }
  printf("Entry Not Found\n");
 }
void search()
 {
   int i,sc;
   printf("Enter Scholar Number\n");
   scanf("%d",&sc);
   for(i=0;i<size;i++)
   if(sch[i]==sc)
   {
     printf("Sch. No.\ts1\ts2\ts3\s4\tTotal\n");
     printf("%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\t%d\n",sch[i],s1[i],s2[i],s3[i],s4[i],tot[i]);
   }
   else
   printf("Entry Not Found\n");
   return;
 }
 void insert()
 {
   printf("Enter Scholar Number and Marks\n");
   scanf("%d%d%d%d%d",&sch[size],&s1[size],&s2[size],&s3[size],&s4[size]);
   tot[size]=s1[size]+s2[size]+s3[size]+s4[size];
   size++;
   printf("Entry Added Successfully\n");
   return;
 }
void sort()
{
  int i,j,temp;
  for(i=0;i<size-1;i++)
  {
    for(j=0;j<size-1-i;j++)
    if(tot[j+1]>tot[j])
    {
    temp=sch[j];
    sch[j]=sch[j+1];
    sch[j+1]=temp;
    temp=s1[j];
    s1[j]=s1[j+1];
    s1[j+1]=temp;
    temp=s2[j];
    s2[j]=s2[j+1];
    s2[j+1]=temp;
    temp=s3[j];
    s3[j]=s3[j+1];
    s3[j+1]=temp;
    temp=s4[j];
    s4[j]=s4[j+1];
    s4[j+1]=temp;
    temp=tot[j];
    tot[j]=tot[j+1];
    tot[j+1]=temp;
    }
  }
  printf ("Sorting Complete\n");
  return;
}

10/23/20, 21:17 - Pratyush: Hii Guys!
This is a callout to all those who want to be better coders and who are ready to put in efforts to improve their coding and development skills. 
Wondering where to begin? No worries. That's where we come in.

*Zenith-The Programming Club* is the only programming club of MANIT. Formed in 2019 by a group of enthusiasts, we aim to improve the coding culture in MANIT and to help and guide the future batches.

We'll stand by you and help you find your interest by providing you with sessions on different development technologies like *Android, Web Dev, and ML.*

At our core lies coding, so we also ensure that you hone your skills of coding by competing in our *ZFT( Zenith fortnightly tests)* which are prepared by keeping the actual coding round of software companies in mind.

To kick start your internship preparation, to hone your coding and development skills, to guide you throughout your journey, and to see you finishing off in style, we are eagerly waiting.
What about you?

*#AllBranches*

Digipplus is an edtech startup based in Newtown, Kolkata. We create academic content for startups. We are catering premier startups of India like Vedantu, Embibe, Gradeup, Toppr & many more.


URL:¬†http://digipplus.com


We have requirements for freelancers for the Subject Matter Expert position for PCB subjects. Below specified is all the details for the work in the form of a questionnaire which can help students understand the work profile.


Objective:¬†To hire 50-100 freelancers/interns per subject for the post of Subject matter expert PCB for 2 months. Preference¬†shall be given to BSc, MSc, Btech, Mtech students.


*What's the job description?*
To write detailed solutions of JEE Mains & NEET level questions as per below mentioned criteria.

*Why should a student join?*
He would be provided with a good stipend & certificate.¬†
*What‚Äôs the tenure of the internship?*
Atleast 2 months.

*What are the criteria for selection?*
Below mentioned are the criteria:
The solution must be unique.
Plagiarism is strictly prohibited.
The Solution must have 250 words.
Solution must be in a conversational tone.Solution must have a hint & note both.
The Solution must be grammatically correct.Equations to be typed using Math type & latex.Diagrams to be drawn wherever required.Question & solution needs to be typed by the writer only.
Solution must be understandable by an average student.
What would Stipend per month?
This is a performance based internship.If the student opts for part time then he is expected to write 6 solutions daily.

 Considering 6 solutions daily and 25 working days, 5000/- for 150 solutions.
Same way for a full time internship, considering 12 solutions daily & 25 working days, it would be 10,000/- per month for 300 solutions.

*What re there any perks available?*
Below mentioned are the perks:Work from home
Time flexibility¬†
Certificate
Opportunity to continue further in vacant positions.
Interested ones should DM on both 9602844519 and legal@digipplus.com informing that you are interested for this position with your name,email id,branch and institute.

11/17/20, 11:40 - Parthesh Cr: Best answer
Either a person sends to 4 people or he doesn't send it. So, let x be the number of persons who sends to 4 people. 100 people didn't send any letter. Except 1 (the initial person) all others (x+100) must have a sender. So, we can write

No. of receivers=4√óNo. of senders+1(Initial person doesn't have a sender)
x+100=4x+1‚üπ3x=99x=33

11/23/20, 17:33 - Pratyush: As we approach the end of 2020, we appreciate your commitment towards educating students and ensuring that the pandemic did not hinder their learning and growth all through the year. We are aware that it took a lot of effort to implement and adapt to a new way of teaching, and we commend your tireless efforts into making it a success.
 
Last month, we wrote to you regarding internship opportunities and an online training program for students of Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology. We are overwhelmed with the response we got from colleges across the country and are happy to be able to contribute to your efforts and add value to the student community.
 
In the past, we have recruited 2 interns from Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology for our Student Partner Internship Program.
 
We had a great experience with your students and wish to extend our sincere thanks to faculty like yourself who made this possible. Click here for the offer letters of students of your college who were hired as interns for Bolt IoT.
 
Innovation Challenge on IoT an ML
 
Last month, quite a few faculties got back to us asking if we could provide for training which includes hardware that would help students to implement their learnings practically. Keeping this in mind, we have decided to launch the third iteration of our Innovation Challenge. I wrote to you a few days ago regarding the same. In this email, I want to share more about the 'Bolt IoT and ML Innovation Challenge.' As part of this challenge, we take a few selected students from some of the prestigious colleges of India, such as Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology and train them on the concepts of IoT and ML. This training is followed by a project competition between them to choose the most innovative students from India.
 
The competition will be judged by some of the experts who have worked at organisations like Amazon. The competition will be an excellent opportunity for the students to showcase their talent and skills at an all India level.
 
What are the Prizes for the students?
1st Place: Cash prize of Rs. 30,000/-
 
2nd Place: Cash prize of Rs. 20,000/-
 
3rd Place: Cash prize of Rs.10,000/-
 
Consolation prizes: 2 Amazon Echo Dots
 
What are the steps for the Bolt IoT and ML Innovation Challenge?
 
Step1: Students will have to answer a scholarship test to qualify for participating in the competition. The qualifying students will also get the IoT and ML training for FREE. They only need to purchase the necessary hardware kit required to build the hands-on projects during the training as well as the competition. To answer the scholarship, students have to visit https://info.boltiot.com/iotmlscholarship
 
Step 2: Our team of developers will train the students on the concepts of IoT and ML via online video training. Upon completion of the training, each student will be issued a certificate which can be submitted in the college/university as per the AICTE rules.
 
Step 3: The students have to build an innovative project in the area of IoT or ML by applying the learnings during the training.
 
Step 4: The winners will be judged by engineers who have worked at prestigious organisations like Amazon.
 
 
Why should students participate?
 
Learning opportunity: Learn IoT and ML for FREE and pay only for the hardware kit required to build various hands-on projects as part of the training and competition. 
 
Certification: Upon completion of the training, the students will be issued a certificate which can be submitted in the college / university as per the AICTE rules.
 
 
What is in it for the colleges?
 
As part of this program, we will be awarding the top 3 colleges with maximum students that qualify for the final round. We will be issuing a certificate and a trophy to each of these colleges.
 
 
How to avail the scholarship and participate in the competition?
To avail the scholarship, the students have to answer a scholarship test and qualify for the same by scoring at-least 70% marks.
This is a short test and will not take more than 10 minutes of the students. This ensures that they can answer it without spending much time if they have exams ongoing.
To answer the scholarship test, students have to visit https://info.boltiot.com/iotmlscholarship
 
 
Other critical points:
The option of a full refund on hardware kit: In case the students are not happy with the hardware or the training offered to them as part of the challenge, then they can return it and get full refund as per the refund policy. This ensures that there is no risk for students or the faculty involved in the process.
 
Terms and conditions
This invitation is only valid for students of 'Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology' and cannot be shared with students of any other institute. We have invited a few prestigious institutes from India for this program.
The last date to avail the scholarship and register for the Innovation Challenge is TOMORROW, 24th of November 2020. Keeping this in mind, please inform your students about the scholarship and competition at earliest.
 
Next action for faculty
We request you to forward the details of this opportunity to your students at the earliest. You may share it with them via Email, Notice Board, WhatsApp and other channels as well. 
 
You can share the link directly on WhatsApp from here: https://info.boltiot.com/iotmlinnovationshare
 
 
We look forward to training the students of 'Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology' on the concepts of IoT and ML as well as their participation in the competition. In case of any queries, please reply to this email or call us on (+91)8881197198 and dial 4 to connect to me. I will be happy to answer any questions that you may have.
 

Regards,
Yeshwant Naik,
DevOps Engineering - Bolt IoT


Scholarship link to participate: https://info.boltiot.com/iotmlscholarship
 
 
Bolt IoT (Inventrom Private Limited)
79, 11th Cross Rd, Binnamangala, Indiranagar
Bengaluru Karnataka 560038 India

1/28/21, 21:33 - Pratyush: DATA FLOW DIAGRAM:

DFD can be drawn to represent the system of different levels of abstraction. Higher-level DFDs are partitioned into low levels-hacking more information and functional elements.
Here, we will take example of 3 levels in the data flow diagram, which are: 0-level DFD, 1-level DFD, and 2-level DFD. 

0-level DFD: 
It‚Äôs designed to be an abstraction view, showing the system as a single process with its relationship to external entities. It represents the entire system as a single bubble with input and output data indicated by incoming/outgoing arrows. 
It is also known as a context diagram.

1-level DFD: 
In 1-level DFD, the context diagram is decomposed into multiple bubbles/processes. In this level, we highlight the main functions of the system and breakdown the high-level process of 0-level DFD into subprocesses. 

2-level DFD: 
2-level DFD goes one step deeper into parts of 1-level DFD. It can be used to plan or record the specific/necessary detail about the system‚Äôs functioning. 





E-R DIAGRAM:

ER-modeling is a data modeling method used in software engineering to produce a conceptual data model of an information system. Diagrams created using this ER-modeling method are called Entity-Relationship Diagrams or ER diagrams or ERDs.

Purpose of ERD
The database analyst gains a better understanding of the data to be contained in the database through the step of constructing the ERD.
The ERD serves as a documentation tool.
Finally, the ERD is used to connect the logical structure of the database to users. In particular, the ERD effectively communicates the logic of the database to users.

Components of an ER Diagrams:
1. Entity
An entity can be a real-world object, either animate or inanimate, that can be merely identifiable. An entity is denoted as a rectangle in an ER diagram. For example, in a school database, students, teachers, classes, and courses offered can be treated as entities. All these entities have some attributes or properties that give them their identity.
2. Attributes
Entities are denoted utilizing their properties, known as attributes. All attributes have values. For example, a student entity may have name, class, and age as attributes.
3. Relationships
The association among entities is known as relationship. Relationships are represented by the diamond-shaped box. For example, an employee works_at a department, a student enrolls in a course. Here, Works_at and Enrolls are called relationships.




COLLABORATION DIAGRAM

A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object.

Collaboration diagrams are created by first identifying the structural elements required to carry out the functionality of an interaction. A model is then built using the relationships between those elements. Several vendors offer software for creating and editing collaboration diagrams.

Notations of a collaboration diagram
A collaboration diagram resembles a flowchart that portrays the roles, functionality and behavior of individual objects as well as the overall operation of the system in real time. The four major components of a collaboration diagram are:

Objects- Objects are shown as rectangles with naming labels inside. The naming label follows the convention of object name: class name. If an object has a property or state that specifically influences the collaboration, this should also be noted.
Actors- Actors are instances that invoke the interaction in the diagram. Each actor has a name and a role, with one actor initiating the entire use case.
Links- Links connect objects with actors and are depicted using a solid line between two elements. Each link is an instance where messages can be sent.
Messages- Messages between objects are shown as a labeled arrow placed near a link. These messages are communications between objects that convey information about the activity and can include the sequence number.
The most important objects are placed in the center of the diagram, with all other participating objects branching off. After all objects are placed, links and messages should be added in between.



UML SEQUENCE DIAGRAM:

UML Sequence Diagrams are interaction diagrams that detail how operations are carried out. They capture the interaction between objects in the context of a collaboration. Sequence Diagrams are time focus and they show the order of the interaction visually by using the vertical axis of the diagram to represent time what messages are sent and when.

Sequence Diagrams captures:
the interaction that takes place in a collaboration that either realizes a use case or an operation (instance diagrams or generic diagrams)
high-level interactions between user of the system and the system, between the system and other systems, or between subsystems (sometimes known as system sequence diagrams)

Purpose of Sequence Diagram
Model high-level interaction between active objects in a system
Model the interaction between object instances within a collaboration that realizes a use case
Model the interaction between objects within a collaboration that realizes an operation
Either model generic interactions (showing all possible paths through the interaction) or specific instances of a interaction (showing just one path through the interaction)
Sequence Diagrams at a Glance
Sequence Diagrams show elements as they interact over time and they are organized according to object (horizontally) and time (vertically):




COMPONENT DIAGRAM:

A component diagram, also known as a UML component diagram, describes the organization and wiring of the physical components in a system. Component diagrams are often drawn to help model implementation details and double-check that every aspect of the system's required functions is covered by planned development. In the first version of UML, components included in these diagrams were physical: documents, database table, files, and executables, all physical elements with a location. In the world of UML 2, these components are less physical and more conceptual stand-alone design elements such as a business process that provides or requires interfaces to interact with other constructs in the system. The physical elements described in UML 1, like files and documents, are now referred to as artifacts. A UML 2 component may contain multiple physical artifacts if they naturally belong together.

Basic Component Diagram Symbols and Notations
Component
A component is a logical unit block of the system, a slightly higher abstraction than classes. It is represented as a rectangle with a smaller rectangle in the upper right corner with tabs or the word written above the name of the component to help distinguish it from a class.
Interface
An interface (small circle or semi-circle on a stick) describes a group of operations used (required) or created (provided) by components. A full circle represents an interface created or provided by the component. A semi-circle represents a required interface, like a person's input.
Dependencies
Draw dependencies among components using dashed arrows.
Port
Ports are represented using a square along the edge of the system or a component. A port is often used to help expose required and provided interfaces of a component.



ACTIVITY DIAGRAM:
An activity diagram visually presents a series of actions or flow of control in a system similar to a flowchart or a data flow diagram. Activity diagrams are often used in business process modeling. They can also describe the steps in a use case diagram. Activities modeled can be sequential and concurrent. In both cases an activity diagram will have a beginning (an initial state) and an end (a final state).

Basic Activity Diagram Notations and Symbols
Initial State or Start Point
A small filled circle followed by an arrow represents the initial action state or the start point for any activity diagram. For activity diagram using swimlanes, make sure the start point is placed in the top left corner of the first column.
Activity or Action State
An action state represents the non-interruptible action of objects. You can draw an action state in SmartDraw using a rectangle with rounded corners.
Action Flow
Action flows, also called edges and paths, illustrate the transitions from one action state to another. They are usually drawn with an arrowed line.
Object Flow
Object flow refers to the creation and modification of objects by activities. An object flow arrow from an action to an object means that the action creates or influences the object. An object flow arrow from an object to an action indicates that the action state uses the object.
Decisions and Branching
A diamond represents a decision with alternate paths. When an activity requires a decision prior to moving on to the next activity, add a diamond between the two activities. The outgoing alternates should be labeled with a condition or guard expression. You can also label one of the paths "else."




USE CASE DIAGRAMS:
Use case diagrams are usually referred to as behavior diagrams used to describe a set of actions (use cases) that some system or systems (subject) should or can perform in collaboration with one or more external users of the system (actors). Each use case should provide some observable and valuable result to the actors or other stakeholders of the system.

DEPLOYMENT DIAGRAMS:
Deployment diagrams are used to visualize the topology of the physical components of a system, where the software components are deployed.

Deployment diagrams are used to describe the static deployment view of a system. Deployment diagrams consist of nodes and their relationships.

Purpose of Deployment Diagrams
The term Deployment itself describes the purpose of the diagram. Deployment diagrams are used for describing the hardware components, where software components are deployed. Component diagrams and deployment diagrams are closely related.

1/28/21, 22:46 - Pratyush: The diagrams are used in SRS report for a better way of interpretation of a project in an organized way. Some of the diagrams used for the enhancement of SRS report are : 1.User case diagram: It is basically used to represent the interaction of user with the system and the specifications of certain use case. 2.Class diagram: It represents structure of a system. It shows the classes in a system, operations and relations between them. 3.Dataflow diagram: It shows the flow of data through system. It is used to visualize data processing. 4.Sequence diagram: It tells the sequence of processes i. e. The order in which they are operated. 5.entity-relationship diagram : It defines the relationship between entities and attributes. Entities are denoted by rectangle, attributes by vowel, relationship by diamond. It gives a clear cut relation between all the entities in a system 6.Activity diagram: It is an advanced graphical representation of activities in a system. It defines the overall work flow of the system

With the help of above diagram we are able to identify the proper functioning of the system and we can predict the limitations and fault in the flow of control of the system. hence we will come to know that what are the functional and non functional requirement of the given system and we can implement on it and in this way the SRS document can be more predictable and understandable. The definitions and uses of the above diagrams are as follows : UML Class Diagram : In software engineering, a class diagram in the Unified Modeling Language is a type of static structure diagram that describes the structure of a system by showing the system's classes, their attributes, operations, and the relationships among objects. Sequence Diagram : A sequence diagram shows object interactions arranged in time sequence. It depicts the objects involved in the scenario and the sequence of messages exchanged between the objects needed to carry out the functionality of the scenario. Use case Diagrams : The purpose of use case diagram is to capture the dynamic aspect of a system. Additional diagrams and documentation can be used to provide a complete functional and technical view of the system. Collaboration Diagram : A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object. Component Diagram : The purpose of a component diagram is to show the relationship between different components in a system Activity Diagram : Activity diagram is another important diagram in UML to describe the dynamic aspects of the system. Activity diagram is basically a flowchart to represent the flow from one activity to another activity. The activity can be described as an operation of the system. Data Flow Diagram : A data-flow diagram is a way of representing a flow of data through a process or a system (usually an information system). The DFD also provides information about the outputs and inputs of each entity and the process itself. E-R Diagram : Entity relationship diagrams are used in software engineering during the planning stages of the software project. They help to identify different system elements and their relationships with each other. 

1. UML Class Diagram - Class diagram is a static diagram. It represents the static view of an application. Class diagram is not only used for visualizing, describing, and documenting different aspects of a system but also for constructing executable code of the software application. Class diagram describes the attributes and operations of a class and also the constraints imposed on the system. The class diagrams are widely used in the modeling of objectoriented systems because they are the only UML diagrams, which can be mapped directly with object-oriented languages. 2. Sequence Diagram- A sequence diagram shows object interactions arranged in time sequence. It depicts the objects involved in the scenario and the sequence of messages exchanged between the objects needed to carry out the functionality of the scenario. Sequence diagrams are typically associated with use case realizations in the logical view of the system under development. Sequence diagrams are sometimes called event diagrams or event scenarios. 3. Use case Diagrams- The purpose of use case diagram is to capture the dynamic aspect of a system. However, this definition is too generic to describe the purpose, as other four diagrams (activity, sequence, collaboration, and Statechart) also have the same purpose. We will look into some specific purpose, which will distinguish it from other four diagrams. 4. Collaboration Diagram- A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object.Collaboration diagrams are created by first identifying the structural elements required to carry out the functionality of an interaction. A model is then built using the relationships between those elements. Several vendors offer software for creating and editing collaboration diagrams. 5. Component Diagram- Component diagrams are different in terms of nature and behavior. Component diagrams are used to model the physical aspects of a system. Now the question is, what are these physical aspects? Physical aspects are the elements such as executables, libraries, files, documents, etc. which reside in a node.Component diagram is a special kind of diagram in UML. The purpose is also different from all other diagrams discussed so far. It does not describe the functionality of the system but it describes the components used to make those functionalities. 6. Activity Diagram- The basic purposes of activity diagrams is similar to other four diagrams. It captures the dynamic behavior of the system. Other four diagrams are used to show the message flow from one object to another but activity diagram is used to show message flow from one activity to another. Activity is a particular operation of the system. Activity diagrams are not only used for visualizing the dynamic nature of a system, but they are also used to construct the executable system by using forward and reverse engineering techniques. The only missing thing in the activity diagram is the message part. 

UML class digram: In software engineering, a class diagram in the Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a type of static structure diagram that describes the structure of a system by showing the system's classes, their attributes, operations (or methods), and the relationships among objects. Sequence diagram: A sequence diagram is a type of interaction diagram because it describes how‚Äîand in what order‚Äîa group of objects works together. These diagrams are used by software developers and business professionals to understand requirements for a new system or to document an existing process. Use case digram : A use case diagram is a dynamic or behavior diagram in UML. Use case diagrams model the functionality of a system using actors and use cases. Use cases are a set of actions, services, and functions that the system needs to perform. Collobarabian digram : A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object. Component diagram : Component diagrams are different in terms of nature and behavior. Component diagrams are used to model the physical aspects of a system. Now the question is, what are these physical aspects? Physical aspects are the elements such as executables, libraries, files, documents, etc. which reside in a node. Component diagrams are used to visualize the organization and relationships among components in a system. These diagrams are also used to make executable systems. Activity digram: An activity diagram visually presents a series of actions or flow of control in a system similar to a flowchart or a data flow diagram. Activity diagrams are often used in business process modeling. They can also describe the steps in a use case diagram. Activities modeled can be sequential and concurrent. Data flow digram : A data-flow diagram is a way of representing a flow of data through a process or a system (usually an information system). The DFD also provides information about the outputs and inputs of each entity and the process itself. ... The data-flow diagram is part of the structured-analysis modeling tools. Deployment Diagram: A UML deployment diagram is a diagram that shows the configuration of run time processing nodes and the components that live on them. Deployment diagrams is a kind of structure diagram used in modeling the physical aspects of an object-oriented system. E-R digram : An Entity Relationship (ER) Diagram is a type of flowchart that illustrates how ‚Äúentities‚Äù such as people, objects or concepts relate to each other within a system. ER Diagrams are most often used to design or debug relational databases in the fields of software engineering, business information systems, education and research. Also known as ERDs or ER Models, they use a defined set of symbols such as rectangles, diamonds, ovals and connecting lines to depict the interconnectedness of entities, relationships and their attributes. They mirror grammatical structure, with entities as nouns and relationships as verbs

In software engineering, a class diagram in the Unified Modeling Language is a type of static structure diagram that describes the structure of a system by showing the system's classes, their attributes, operations, and the relationships among objects. A sequence diagram shows object interactions arranged in time sequence. It depicts the objects involved in the scenario and the sequence of messages exchanged between the objects needed to carry out the functionality of the scenario. A use case diagram at its simplest is a representation of a user's interaction with the system that shows the relationship between the user and the different use cases in which the user is involved. A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object. A component diagram, also known as a UML component diagram, describes the organization and wiring of the physical components in a system. Activity diagrams are graphical representations of workflows of stepwise activities and actions with support for choice, iteration and concurrency. A data-flow diagram is a way of representing a flow of data through a process or a system (usually an information system). The DFD also provides information about the outputs and inputs of each entity and the process itself. The data-flow diagram is part of the structured-analysis modeling tools. A deployment diagram in the Unified Modeling Language models the physical deployment of artifacts on nodes. To describe a web site, for example, a deployment diagram would show what hardware components exist, what software components run on each node, and how the different pieces are connected. ER Diagram stands for Entity Relationship Diagram, also known as ERD is a diagram that displays the relationship of entity sets stored in a database. In other words, ER diagrams help to explain the logical structure of databases. All information is cited mostly from wikipedia under the related subheadings.

Sequence flow diagram Class diagram ER diagram Activity diagram Use case diagram Data flow diagram Explanations as understood of various diagrams given above-- Sequence flow diagram It is an interaction diagram that illustrates how processes will be operated. It is related with Use case diagram of system under development. Class diagram It is Structure diagram that represents structure of system by showing classes of system their operations and relationships among objects. ER diagram These diagrams help in representing ideas in form of entities and relationships. It shows conceptual framework of a system. Activity diagram These are graphical representation of workflows of stepwise activities and actions with support for iteration, concurrency etc. Use Case diagram It is simplest representation of users interaction with system and specifications of particular use case in which user is involved. It can be drawn in various types as per user's interaction. Data flow diagram Shows graphical representation of flow of data through information system. It creates overview of system which can be elaborated later. 

DATA FLOW DIAGRAM: DFD can be drawn to represent the system of different levels of abstraction. Higher-level DFDs are partitioned into low levels-hacking more information and functional elements. Here, we will take example of 3 levels in the data flow diagram, which are: 0-level DFD, 1-level DFD, and 2-level DFD. 0-level DFD: It‚Äôs designed to be an abstraction view, showing the system as a single process with its relationship to external entities. It represents the entire system as a single bubble with input and output data indicated by incoming/outgoing arrows. It is also known as a context diagram. 1-level DFD: In 1-level DFD, the context diagram is decomposed into multiple bubbles/processes. In this level, we highlight the main functions of the system and breakdown the high-level process of 0-level DFD into subprocesses. 2-level DFD: 2-level DFD goes one step deeper into parts of 1-level DFD. It can be used to plan or record the specific/necessary detail about the system‚Äôs functioning. E-R DIAGRAM: ER-modeling is a data modeling method used in software engineering to produce a conceptual data model of an information system. Diagrams created using this ER-modeling method are called Entity-Relationship Diagrams or ER diagrams or ERDs. Purpose of ERD The database analyst gains a better understanding of the data to be contained in the database through the step of constructing the ERD. The ERD serves as a documentation tool. Finally, the ERD is used to connect the logical structure of the database to users. In particular, the ERD effectively communicates the logic of the database to users. Components of an ER Diagrams: 1. Entity An entity can be a real-world object, either animate or inanimate, that can be merely identifiable. An entity is denoted as a rectangle in an ER diagram. For example, in a school database, students, teachers, classes, and courses offered can be treated as entities. All these entities have some attributes or properties that give them their identity. 2. Attributes Entities are denoted utilizing their properties, known as attributes. All attributes have values. For example, a student entity may have name, class, and age as attributes. 3. Relationships The association among entities is known as relationship. Relationships are represented by the diamond-shaped box. For example, an employee works_at a department, a student enrolls in a course. Here, Works_at and Enrolls are called relationships. COLLABORATION DIAGRAM A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object. Collaboration diagrams are created by first identifying the structural elements required to carry out the functionality of an interaction. A model is then built using the relationships between those elements. Several vendors offer software for creating and editing collaboration diagrams. Notations of a collaboration diagram A collaboration diagram resembles a flowchart that portrays the roles, functionality and behavior of individual objects as well as the overall operation of the system in real time. The four major components of a collaboration diagram are: Objects- Objects are shown as rectangles with naming labels inside. The naming label follows the convention of object name: class name. If an object has a property or state that specifically influences the collaboration, this should also be noted. Actors- Actors are instances that invoke the interaction in the diagram. Each actor has a name and a role, with one actor initiating the entire use case. Links- Links connect objects with actors and are depicted using a solid line between two elements. Each link is an instance where messages can be sent. Messages- Messages between objects are shown as a labeled arrow placed near a link. These messages are communications between objects that convey information about the activity and can include the sequence number. The most important objects are placed in the center of the diagram, with all other participating objects branching off. After all objects are placed, links and messages should be added in between. UML SEQUENCE DIAGRAM: UML Sequence Diagrams are interaction diagrams that detail how operations are carried out. They capture the interaction between objects in the context of a collaboration. Sequence Diagrams are time focus and they show the order of the interaction visually by using the vertical axis of the diagram to represent time what messages are sent and when. Sequence Diagrams captures: the interaction that takes place in a collaboration that either realizes a use case or an operation (instance diagrams or generic diagrams) high-level interactions between user of the system and the system, between the system and other systems, or between subsystems (sometimes known as system sequence diagrams) Purpose of Sequence Diagram Model high-level interaction between active objects in a system Model the interaction between object instances within a collaboration that realizes a use case Model the interaction between objects within a collaboration that realizes an operation Either model generic interactions (showing all possible paths through the interaction) or specific instances of a interaction (showing just one path through the interaction) Sequence Diagrams at a Glance Sequence Diagrams show elements as they interact over time and they are organized according to object (horizontally) and time (vertically): COMPONENT DIAGRAM: A component diagram, also known as a UML component diagram, describes the organization and wiring of the physical components in a system. Component diagrams are often drawn to help model implementation details and double-check that every aspect of the system's required functions is covered by planned development. In the first version of UML, components included in these diagrams were physical: documents, database table, files, and executables, all physical elements with a location. In the world of UML 2, these components are less physical and more conceptual stand-alone design elements such as a business process that provides or requires interfaces to interact with other constructs in the system. The physical elements described in UML 1, like files and documents, are now referred to as artifacts. A UML 2 component may contain multiple physical artifacts if they naturally belong together. Basic Component Diagram Symbols and Notations Component A component is a logical unit block of the system, a slightly higher abstraction than classes. It is represented as a rectangle with a smaller rectangle in the upper right corner with tabs or the word written above the name of the component to help distinguish it from a class. Interface An interface (small circle or semi-circle on a stick) describes a group of operations used (required) or created (provided) by components. A full circle represents an interface created or provided by the component. A semi-circle represents a required interface, like a person's input. Dependencies Draw dependencies among components using dashed arrows. Port Ports are represented using a square along the edge of the system or a component. A port is often used to help expose required and provided interfaces of a component. ACTIVITY DIAGRAM: An activity diagram visually presents a series of actions or flow of control in a system similar to a flowchart or a data flow diagram. Activity diagrams are often used in business process modeling. They can also describe the steps in a use case diagram. Activities modeled can be sequential and concurrent. In both cases an activity diagram will have a beginning (an initial state) and an end (a final state). Basic Activity Diagram Notations and Symbols Initial State or Start Point A small filled circle followed by an arrow represents the initial action state or the start point for any activity diagram. For activity diagram using swimlanes, make sure the start point is placed in the top left corner of the first column. Activity or Action State An action state represents the non-interruptible action of objects. You can draw an action state in SmartDraw using a rectangle with rounded corners. Action Flow Action flows, also called edges and paths, illustrate the transitions from one action state to another. They are usually drawn with an arrowed line. Object Flow Object flow refers to the creation and modification of objects by activities. An object flow arrow from an action to an object means that the action creates or influences the object. An object flow arrow from an object to an action indicates that the action state uses the object. Decisions and Branching A diamond represents a decision with alternate paths. When an activity requires a decision prior to moving on to the next activity, add a diamond between the two activities. The outgoing alternates should be labeled with a condition or guard expression. You can also label one of the paths "else." USE CASE DIAGRAMS: Use case diagrams are usually referred to as behavior diagrams used to describe a set of actions (use cases) that some system or systems (subject) should or can perform in collaboration with one or more external users of the system (actors). Each use case should provide some observable and valuable result to the actors or other stakeholders of the system. DEPLOYMENT DIAGRAMS: Deployment diagrams are used to visualize the topology of the physical components of a system, where the software components are deployed. Deployment diagrams are used to describe the static deployment view of a system. Deployment diagrams consist of nodes and their relationships. Purpose of Deployment Diagrams The term Deployment itself describes the purpose of the diagram. Deployment diagrams are used for describing the hardware components, where software components are deployed. Component diagrams and deployment diagrams are closely related.

1.UML class diagram: In software engineering, a class diagram in the Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a type of static structure diagram that describes the structure of a system by showing the system's classes, their attributes, operations (or methods), and the relationships among objects. 1. Shows static structure of classifiers in a system 2.Diagram provides a basic notation for other structure diagrams prescribed by UML 3.Helpful for developers and other team members too 4.Business Analysts can use class diagrams to model systems from a business perspective 2.Sequence Diagram: UML Sequence Diagrams are interaction diagrams that detail how operations are carried out. They capture the interaction between objects in the context of a collaboration. Sequence Diagrams are time focus and they show the order of the interaction visually by using the vertical axis of the diagram to represent time what messages are sent and when. Model high-level interaction between active objects in a system Model the interaction between object instances within a collaboration that realizes a use case. 3. Use case Diagrams: Use case diagrams consists of actors, use cases and their relationships. The diagram is used to model the system/subsystem of an application. A single use case diagram captures a particular functionality of a system.Used to gather the requirements of a system.Used to get an outside view of a system. Identify the external and internal factors influencing the system. 4.Collaboration Diagram: The collaboration diagram is used to show the relationship between the objects in a system. Both the sequence and the collaboration diagrams represent the same information but differently. Instead of showing the flow of messages, it depicts the architecture of the object residing in the system as it is based on object-oriented programming. An object consists of several features. Multiple objects present in the system are connected to each other. The collaboration diagram, which is also known as a communication diagram, is used to portray the object's architecture in the system. 5.Component Diagram: Component diagrams are different in terms of nature and behavior. Component diagrams are used to model the physical aspects of a system. Component diagrams are used to visualize the organization and relationships among components in a system. These diagrams are also used to make executable systems.Visualize the components of a system.Construct executables by using forward and reverse engineering. 6.Activity Diagram: Activity diagram is basically a flowchart to represent the flow from one activity to another activity. The activity can be described as an operation of the system. The control flow is drawn from one operation to another. This flow can be sequential, branched, or concurrent. Activity diagrams deal with all type of flow control by using different elements such as fork, join, etc. 7.Deployment Diagram: A deployment diagram is a UML diagram type that shows the execution architecture of a system, including nodes such as hardware or software execution environments, and the middleware connecting them. Deployment diagrams are typically used to visualize the physical hardware and software of a system. Using it you can understand how the system will be physically deployed on the hardware. Deployment diagrams help model the hardware topology of a system compared to other UML diagram types which mostly outline the logical components of a system. 8.E-R Diagram: Helps you to define terms related to entity relationship modeling Provide a preview of how all your tables should connect, what fields are going to be on each table Helps to describe entities, attributes, relationships ER diagrams are translatable into relational tables which allows you to build databases quickly ER diagrams can be used by database designers as a blueprint for implementing data in specific software applications The database designer gains a better understanding of the information to be contained in the database with the help of ERP diagram ERD Diagram allows you to communicate with the logical structure of the database to users. 9.Data-flow Diagram: Data flow diagrams are used to graphically represent the flow of data in a business information system. It describes the processes that are involved in a system to transfer data from the input to the file storage and reports generation. Data flow diagrams can be divided into logical and physical. The logical data flow diagram describes flow of data through a system to perform certain functionality of a business. The physical data flow diagram describes the implementation of the logical data flow.

UML Class Diagram - Class diagram is a static diagram. It represents the static view of an application. Class diagram is not only used for visualizing, describing, and documenting different aspects of a system but also for constructing executable code of the software application. Sequence Diagram - A sequence diagram is a type of interaction diagram because it describes how and in what order a group of objects works together. These diagrams are used by software developers and business professionals to understand requirements for a new system or to document an existing process. Use Case Diagram - A use case diagram at its simplest is a representation of a user's interaction with the system that shows the relationship between the user and the different use cases in which the user is involved. Collaboration Diagram - A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object. Component Diagram - describes the organization and wiring of the physical components in a system. Component diagrams are often drawn to help model implementation details and double-check that every aspect of the system's required functions is covered by planned development. Activity Diagram - An activity diagram is a behavioral diagram i.e. it depicts the behavior of a system. An activity diagram portrays the control flow from a start point to a finish point showing the various decision paths that exist while the activity is being executed. Data Flow Diagram - A DFD shows flow of data through the system. DFD captures how transformation occurs from input to output as data moves through the transforms. It views system as transforming inputs to outputs. Deployment Diagram - A deployment diagram is a UML diagram type that shows the execution architecture of a system, including nodes such as hardware or software execution environments, and the middleware connecting them. Deployment diagrams are typically used to visualize the physical hardware and software of a system. E-R Diagram - An entity‚Äìrelationship model describes interrelated things of interest in a specific domain of knowledge. A basic ER model is composed of entity types and specifies relationships that can exist between entities.

1. Dataflow diagram: It is a graphical representation of the flow of data through an information system, modeling its process aspects. Often they are a preliminary step used to create an overview of the system which can later be elaborated. 2. Use case diagram : It is the simplest representation of user's interaction with system and specification of a particular use case, it can be drawn in various types by the user which can interact with the system. 3. Sequence diagram : It is an interaction diagram that represents how process will be operated with one another in an order. This are related with the use case diagram logically of a system which is under development. 4. Class diagram : In unified modelling language, class diagram is a type of structure diagram that represents system structure by showing the classes of a system their operations and relationships among objects. 5. Activity diagram: Activity diagram are graphical representation of work flows of stopwise activities and action with support for choice and iteration and concurrency. Activity show the overall flow of control. 6. Entity relation diagram: An entity relation model is a data model for describing the data or information aspects of a business domain or its process required in an abstract way that lends itself to ultimately being implemented in a database such as a relational database.

Sequence diagrams Sequence diagrams is used by developers, model the interactions between objects in a single use case. They illustrate how the different parts of a system interact with each other to carry out a function, and the order in which the interactions occur when a particular use case is executed. E-R Diagram ER diagrams constitute a very useful framework for creating and manipulating databases. First, ER diagrams are easy to understand and do not require a person to undergo extensive training to be able to work with it efficiently and accurately. This means that designers can use ER diagrams to easily communicate with developers, customers, and end users, regardless of their IT proficiency. Second, ER diagrams are readily translatable into relational tables which can be used to quickly build databases. In addition, ER diagrams can directly be used by database developers as the blueprint for implementing data in specific software applications. Lastly, ER diagrams may be applied in other contexts such as describing the different relationships and operations within an organization. Data Flow Diagram It is a preliminary step used to create an overview of the system that can later be elaborated Component diagram The purpose of a component diagram is to show the relationship between different components in a system. For the purpose of UML 2.0, the term "component" refers to a module of classes that represent independent systems or subsystems with the ability to interface with the rest of the system. 

The diagrams: Class Diagram: The purpose of class diagram is to model the static view of an application. It describes the responsibilities of a system. These diagrams can drawn after considering a lot of properties. It also includes Activity Diagram and Sequence diagram, giving the sequence flow of the application. Use case Diagrams: The purpose of use case diagram is to capture the dynamic aspect of a system. It shows the behavior of software during running. It is used to gather the requirements of a system. It helps us identify the Internal and External factors influencing the system. Collaboration Diagram: A collaboration diagram, also known as a communication diagram, is an illustration of the relationships and interactions among software objects in the Unified Modeling Language (UML). These diagrams can be used to portray the dynamic behavior of a particular use case and define the role of each object. It describes the message flow in the system and describe the structural organization of the objects. It also describe the interaction among objects. Component Diagram: Component diagrams are used to model the physical aspects of a system. Physical aspects are the elements such as executables, libraries, files, documents. A single component diagram cannot represent the entire system but a collection of diagrams is used to represent the whole. It helps to visualize the components of a system. Activity Diagram: An activity diagram depicts the behavior of a system. Activity diagram is basically a flowchart to represent the flow from one activity to another activity. The activity can be described as an operation of the system. It describes the sequence from one activity to another. Data Flow Diagram: Data Flow Diagram of a system shows the flow of data of the system or process. It does not contain flow and no loops. They belong to structured analysis modelling tools. It helps us to understand the functioning and the limits of a system. Deployment Diagram: Deployment diagrams are used to visualize the topology of the physical components of a system(Hardware), where the software components are deployed. Deployment diagrams are used to describe the static deployment view of a system. It also describes the runtime processes.

1. data flow diagram Data flow diagram is a representation of flow of data in a software. These type of diagram are very help to guess the flow of data and easy to explain in this way also to client. It is capable of illustrating incoming data flow, outgoing data flow and store data. Data flow diagram describes anything about how data flows through the system. 2. Logical data flow diagram Logical data flow focuses on the system process. It illustrates how data flows in the system. Logical DFD is used in various organizations for the smooth running of system. Like in a Banking software system, it is used to describe how data is moved from one entity to another. 3. physical data flow diagram Physical data flow diagram shows how the data flow is actually implemented in the system. Physical DFD is more specific and close to implementation. 4.Sequence Diagram A sequence diagram is an interaction diagram. From the name, it is clear that the diagram deals with some sequences, which are the sequence of messages flowing from one object to another. Interaction among the components of a system is very important from implementation and execution perspective. Sequence diagram is used to visualize the sequence of calls in a system to perform a specific functionality. 5. Collaboration Diagram Collaboration diagram is another form of interaction diagram. It represents the structural organization of a system and the messages sent/received. Structural organization consists of objects and links. The purpose of collaboration diagram is similar to sequence diagram. However, the specific purpose of collaboration diagram is to visualize the organization of objects and their interaction. 6. State chart Diagram Any real-time system is expected to be reacted by some kind of internal/external events. These events are responsible for state change of the system. Statechart diagram is used to represent the event driven state change of a system. It basically describes the state change of a class, interface, etc. State chart diagram is used to visualize the reaction of a system by internal/external factors. 7. Activity Diagram Activity diagram describes the flow of control in a system. It consists of activities and links. The flow can be sequential, concurrent, or branched. Activities are nothing but the functions of a system. Numbers of activity diagrams are prepared to capture the entire flow in a system. Activity diagrams are used to visualize the flow of controls in a system. This is prepared to have an idea of how the system will work when executed

2/5/21, 19:43 - Pratyush: Are you worried about your attendance??
Do you forget to submit your assignments on time??
Are you not able to find notes when required??
Do you miss important announcements made by teachers??
Do some notices goes unnoticed??

*There we go MANIT+ is here!!!!*
Specially designed and developed for students of MANIT catering to all the needs of students.
MANIT+ has features which help you manage your attendance day wise for each subject. Assignment section where each one of you can upload assignments given by teachers so that all of us can keep track of which assignments are due and which are completed.
Recieve Notifications everytime a new assignment is uploaded and also a *day before the submission date*.
Also anyone can upload notes given by teachers so that students who missed the class will not miss the notes.

All your notes at one place isn't it helpful??
All your assignments at one place isn't it a major stress buster for everyone. 
All the upcoming and past events at one place so that you don't need to scroll through long chats of whatsapp groups won't it be helpful!! 

The major perk of MANIT+ is to save your time from roaming across different Apps for different purposes. No need to use individual Apps for managing your attendance, searching for notes and assignments, looking for past, ongoing and upcoming events and notices too.

So what are you waiting for??
Download the app and register yourself with your registered email id  and start using and contributing..

Don't forget to give your valuable suggestions so that we can make MANIT+ more helpful for all of us in upcoming days.
The best a student can get..üòâ

The registration process for the Code For Good 2021 is now open!

Please forward the below registration details with your students and ask them to submit their formal application for the Software Engineer Program on our Careers page at the earliest. The Code For Good event is the only means this year by which the students can apply for the Software Engineer Program (SEP) at JP Morgan Chase & Co. We will not be coming to campus this year for on-campus hiring for the Software Engineer Program. 

Eligibility Criteria for registration for the Software Engineer Program:

‚Ä¢           2022 Batch Pass-outs [eligible for Full-Time Analyst opportunity in 2022] or 2023 Batch Pass-outs [eligible for Internship opportunity in 2022, and later eligible for Full-Time Analyst opportunity in 2023 based on performance during internship]

‚Ä¢           Degree ‚Äì B.Tech / BE / MCA

‚Ä¢           Streams / Specialization ‚Äì Computer Science, Information Science/ Information Technology, Electronics, Electrical, Electronics & Telecommunications

‚Ä¢           Backlogs ‚Äì No current backlogs, Graduation in first attempt

‚Ä¢           Education Gap  ‚Äì Not more than 1 year

‚Ä¢           A well-rounded academic background with minimum aggregate 7 CGPA until date

‚Ä¢           Knowledge of IT programming languages (Java, Python, JavaScript, Go and other programming languages, networks and databases)

‚Ä¢           Strong interpersonal and communication skills

‚Ä¢           Ability to thrive in a fast-paced, collaborative environment

‚Ä¢           Relevant internship experience and leadership in school or community organization

‚Ä¢           Fluency in English is essential


Registration Links:

¬∑         The students from the 2022 graduating batch, who are applying for the Full-Time Analyst opportunity in 2022, should click here https://jpmc.fa.oraclecloud.com/hcmUI/CandidateExperience/en/sites/CX_1001/job/210072211/?utm_medium=jobshare   to register themselves.

¬∑         The students from the 2023 graduating batch, who are applying for the Internship opportunity in 2022, should click here  https://jpmc.fa.oraclecloud.com/hcmUI/CandidateExperience/en/sites/CX_1001/job/210071042/?utm_medium=jobshare   to register themselves.

 

Registration Dates:

¬∑         Registration to the Code For Good 2021 for both [2022 & 2023] graduating batches starts today.

¬∑         The last day for registration for students from the 2023 graduating batch, who are applying for the Internship opportunity in 2022, is 19th February 2021. Their online test is on 20th February 2021.

¬∑         The last day for registration for students from the 2022 graduating batch, who are applying for the Full-Time Analyst opportunity in 2022, is 26th February 2021. Their online test is on 27th February 2021.

 

Selection Process:

¬∑         Eligible students register themselves on the JP Morgan Chase Careers page as per the given deadlines [as mentioned above].

¬∑         All eligible students appear for an online coding test. The coding test for the 2023 Batch is scheduled on 20th February 2021. The coding test for the 2022 Batch is scheduled on 27th February 2021. We will share further details on the online tests at a later stage.

¬∑         All eligible students appear for a video interview.

¬∑         JP Morgan Chase announces the final participant shortlist for the Code For Good events

 

Important Points to Know:

1. Click ‚ÄòApply Now‚Äô and sign in with your JPMC career site username and associated personal email address. In case of you have previously signed up with your college email address, please edit the email address to your personal one before proceeding with this application. If you do not recall your password click forgot your password and follow the instructions

2.  Complete your application. If you are currently using an ‚Äò.edu‚Äô email address please update it to a personal non ‚Äò.edu‚Äô email address. Failure to do so could cause delays in you receiving updates regarding your candidacy. You will be required to attach your resume with a Photograph on the right-hand/left-hand corner [Mandatory], kindly update your prior internship experience with other skills [optional].

3. In case your campus does not appear in the application form, please select ‚Äòother‚Äô and mention the campus in the free text field.

4. Click ‚ÄúSubmit‚Äù to officially submit your application ‚Äì a confirmation will be sent to the email address on your account when your application has been received

6/15/21, 20:46 - Pratyush: _"In the depth of winter, I finally learned that within me lay an invincible summer. "_
-Albert Camus

Not a single soul in MANIT was left untouched by the events that transpired this year. It was a long, dark winter. The destruction of normality left every one of us searching for answers.

What horizons lay ahead? What does it mean to have a "New Normal?" 

We present you this year's annual magazine, an attempt by us at rethinking horizons. It is a tribute to every MANITian, everyone who dared to think the answers to some of the most fundamental questions of human existence. 

Come, discover the summer that lies within you.

7/20/21, 07:57 - Pratyush: *Internship Opportunities for Engineering Students*

This is to inform  that the Ministry of Heavy Industries, Government of India has supported the Technology Innovation Platforms (TIPs) for promoting the innovation in manufacturing through the collaboration of the experts (academia and Industry), entrepreneurs, start ups and students in the country.

As a part of these platforms, the students of engineering degree programs are given an opportunity to work on practically relevant problems at four different institutions: AMTDC-IITM, ARAI, CMTI, and ICAT  through an internship program. The details of this program are provided in the  document attached. 


We will appreciate if you can publicise the internship opportunity to the students of your Institution/College through email or otherwise. 

We will be happy to provide any other details with regard to this initiative under the Technology Innovation Platforms.

Fill this form by tonight. 23/08/2021 11:59 PM

Your Team Number is the Serial Number of *Team Member A* in your team. 
*Serial Number is NOT your scholar number.* It is written in the Minor Name List Excel. 

For eg: If your team is A: (SNo 4) B: (SNo 32) C: (SNo 43) D: (SNo 70).

9/18/21, 13:58 - Parthesh Cr: Factwise Test Details: 
Zoom meeting details  

Meeting ID: 501 784 1285  

Passcode: 111222  

Steps to enter the test:  

Open Zoom and set your display name to First Name, Last Name, Student ID; eg: Jyothi Kapur 43675684. Please enter on time as the meeting will be locked 5 minutes after the scheduled time for this test. 
 

Enter the Zoom Meeting ID and password from this email, and double check that your webcam is on. Please do this before the next step, otherwise we might not be able to count you in. 
 

After you have been let in to the Zoom meeting, download and open the *.seb file from this email.  

In case it asks you for a configure change, just accept it.  

If Zoom re-opens, you can just minimize it. 
 
The test platform will open in the browser, and all other open processes on your computer will be shut down, except for Zoom. Register on the platform using your full name and email address.

Take a deep breath and get ready to ace the challenge! The challenge timer begins once you register and start the test.

11/6/21, 12:57 - Parthesh Cr: *Summer Research Fellowships 2022* for Students and Teachers by *Indian Science Academies* (IAS)

Following are eligibility criteria:
Students

a) Applicants should be studying in one of the following:
BS / BSc / BVSc (II year only)
BPharm (III and IV years only)
BE / BTech / BCA (II and III years only)
BArch (II, III and IV years only)
MS / MSc / MVSc / MPharm (I year only)
ME / MTech / MCA / MArch (I year only)
(5-year integrated) MS / MSc /MTech / MBBS (II, III, IV years only)
PharmD (III, IV years only)
(dual degree) BTech + MTech (II, III, IV years only)
(dual degree) BE + MSc (II, III, IV years only)
(dual degree) BS + MS (II, III, IV years only)
Integrated PhD (I, II years only)
MSc Tech (I, II years only)

Teachers

b) Teachers must be teaching in a College/University.

2) The minimum percentage of average marks in core subjects only (i.e. excluding languages) from X std. up to post-graduation (whichever years completed) should be 65% or above for students.The minimum Percentage of average marks does not apply for teachers.

3) PhD students are not eligible.

4) Applicants who have availed the Academies fellowship twice before are not eligible to apply.

More details at 

https://t.co/hjW2XtqXT2 

Last date to apply 30th November 2021
